data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work without requiring an `unsafe` context — you just write:

```csharp
Span<nint>  s = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> u = stackalloc nuint[4];
```

On this 64-bit system, each element is **8 bytes**. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types backed by `IntPtr`/`UIntPtr`.
